'''John L. Noseworthy''' is a [[Canadian]] [[accountant]] and [[politician]] who served as [[Auditor General of Newfoundland and Labrador]] from April 25, 2002 till July 30, 2011.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ag.gov.nl.ca/ag/history.htm |title=History |author= |date=2011 |work= |publisher=Office of the Auditor General - Newfoundland and Labrador |accessdate=7 March 2011}}</ref><ref name="appointment">{{cite news|title=The following statement was issued today by Premier Roger Grimes. It was also read in the House of Assembly:|url=http://www.releases.gov.nl.ca/releases/2002/exec/0425n05.htm|accessdate=16 August 2011|newspaper=Government of Newfoundland and Labrador|date=25 April 2002}}</ref> Noseworthy was the [[Progressive Conservative Party of Newfoundland and Labrador]] candidate for the district of [[Signal Hill-Quidi Vidi]] in the [[Newfoundland and Labrador general election, 2011|October 2011 provincial election]] losing to [[New Democratic Party]] candidate [[Lorraine Michael]].<ref name="former ag">{{cite news|title=Former AG to challenge NDP leader in N.L. election|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/newfoundland-labrador/story/2011/08/19/nl-ag-ndp-819.html|accessdate=20 August 2011|newspaper=Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|date=19 August 2011}}</ref>
Noseworthy began his career with government in 1981 as a senior auditor in the Department of the Auditor General. He held positions of Auditor Manager, Audit Principal and Deputy Auditor General. In April 2002, Premier Roger Grimes gave notice that he would move a motion in the [[Newfoundland House of Assembly|House of Assembly]] appointing Noseworthy as successor to [[Beth Marshall]], which subsequently passed.<ref name="appointment"/>
Noseworthy is a past Board member of the Council of the Institute of Chartered Accountants of Newfoundland and Labrador, past Chair of the Canadian Council of Legislative Auditors Strategic Issues Group, and past Chair of the Planning and Coordinating Committee of the Canadian Council of Legislative Auditors. In 2002 Noseworthy was awarded the [[Queenâs Golden Jubilee Medal]] for outstanding public service.<ref>{{cite web|title=John Noseworthy|url=http://www.dunderdale2011.ca/our-team/2011-candidates/john-noseworthy/|publisher=Progressive Conservative Party of Newfoundland and Labrador|accessdate=26 August 2011}}</ref>
==Politics== On June 22, 2011, John Noseworthy announced via [[Twitter]] that he was retiring from his position as Auditor General effective July 31, 2011, 13 months before his 10 year term as Auditor General was up.<ref>{{cite news|title=Noseworthy retiring as auditor general|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/newfoundland-labrador/story/2011/06/22/nl-noseworthy-ag-retires-622.html|accessdate=16 August 2011|newspaper=Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|date=22 June 2011}}</ref> His name was brought up as a candidate for the leadership of the [[Liberal Party of Newfoundland and Labrador]] upon the resignation of [[Yvonne Jones]], but on August 8, 2011 he announced he was offered the job of Liberal leader but declined. On August 16, 2011, he announced he was seeking the Progressive Conservative Party nomination in the district of Signal Hill-Quidi Vidi for the October 2011 provincial election.<ref>{{cite news|title=Noseworthy plans Tory run against NDP leader|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/newfoundland-labrador/story/2011/08/16/nl-noseworthy-tories-nomination-816.html|accessdate=16 August 2011|newspaper=Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|date=16 August 2011}}</ref> On August 19, he was acclaimed as the party's candidate for the district, which is currently held by [[New Democratic Party of Newfoundland and Labrador|New Democratic Party]] leader [[Lorraine Michael]].<ref name="former ag"/>
